{"id":242,"date":"2012-10-07T12:05:57","date_gmt":"2012-10-07T16:05:57","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/?p=242"},"modified":"2020-02-18T16:33:29","modified_gmt":"2020-02-18T21:33:29","slug":"have-saws-will-travel","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/2012\/10\/07\/have-saws-will-travel\/","title":{"rendered":"Have Saws, Will Travel"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>A few Saturdays ago, I attended the Midwest Tool Collector&#8217;s Association (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.mwtca.org\/\">MWTCA<\/a>) tool meet, and finished acquiring all the tools listed in The Anarchist&#8217;s Tool Chest (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.lostartpress.com\/The_Anarchist_s_Tool_Chest_p\/bk-atc.htm\">ATC<\/a>) book, yea!\u00a0 I can fit almost all of my tools in my traveling version of the ATC, except my saws.\u00a0 So I got to thinking that I currently did not have a good way to store or transport my saws.\u00a0\u00a0 During the MWTCA tool meet, I saw an old military ammo crate that would have almost done the trick.\u00a0 I did not buy the crate&#8230;because I thought it would be more fun to build my own!<\/p>\n<p>On Sunday, my daughter and I went to the local home center to pick up a 1x10x8 board.\u00a0 Before I actually started to cut wood,\u00a0 I needed to prototype the till to make sure it would work for me.\u00a0 I read in the ATC that Chris Schwarz needed to tinker a bit with his design before committing it to wood, so I fashioned a version from scrap wood, roughly following Chris&#8217;s design in the ATC.\u00a0 The big difference in mine was that I decided to make it for 7 saws instead of 4.\u00a0 My decision to build a bigger one was based on this reasoning:\u00a0 If I take it to a class that is not saw-focused, I can just load it with the standard 4 saws:\u00a0 Rip, Crosscut, Dovetail and Carcass.\u00a0 If I take it to a saw sharpening class, I can load it up with multiple saws to be worked on.\u00a0 Plus, at home, it will maximize storage.<\/p>\n<p>Here is a pic of my prototype saw till.\u00a0 It is smaller than the actual till, but it was a great proof of concept.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_275\" style=\"width: 650px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><a href=\"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/proto_till1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-275\" class=\" wp-image-275 \" title=\"proto_till1\" src=\"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/proto_till1-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"853\" srcset=\"https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/proto_till1-768x1024.jpg 768w, https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/proto_till1-225x300.jpg 225w, https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/proto_till1.jpg 960w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" \/><\/a><p id=\"caption-attachment-275\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Prototype dimensions are 6&#8243;W x 6&#8243;H x 3\/4&#8243; with 3\/4&#8243; saw cuts for the saws and a offset 2 1\/2 radius circle. The two till boards are spaced 6 1\/4&#8243; apart<\/p><\/div>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>After using the prototype till for a while, I designed the box around it, while allowing for some extra room.\u00a0 I made my production till 8&#8243; wide and 8&#8243; tall and made of pine.\u00a0 I made my saw cuts 1 3\/8&#8243; apart, keeping the saw handles and blades 5\/16&#8243; apart at their closest on each side.<\/p>\n<p>So, here is my saw till.\u00a0 The 3&#8243; radius semi-circle cut in the top, allows the back saws to be level with the panel saws.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_271\" style=\"width: 650px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><a href=\"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/saw_till_detail.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-271\" class=\"size-large wp-image-271\" title=\"saw_till_detail\" src=\"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/saw_till_detail-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" srcset=\"https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/saw_till_detail-1024x768.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/saw_till_detail-300x225.jpg 300w, https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/saw_till_detail.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" \/><\/a><p id=\"caption-attachment-271\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Production dimensions are 8&#8243;W x 8&#8243;H x 3\/4&#8243; with 1 3\/8&#8243; saw cuts for the saws and a 3 radius circle. The two till boards are spaced 6 1\/4&#8243; apart<\/p><\/div>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>Below is a pic of one of my finished dovetailed corners of the saw box.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_272\" style=\"width: 650px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><a href=\"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/dovetail_corner1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-272\" class=\"size-large wp-image-272\" title=\"dovetail_corner1\" src=\"http:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/dovetail_corner1-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"853\" srcset=\"https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/dovetail_corner1-768x1024.jpg 768w, https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/dovetail_corner1-225x300.jpg 225w, https:\/\/oldetoolworkshop.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2012\/09\/dovetail_corner1.jpg 960w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" \/><\/a><p id=\"caption-attachment-272\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Perspective of one finished dovetail corner with prototype till &#8220;inside&#8221; it<\/p><\/div>\n<p>More to come soon &#8230;<\/p>\n<p>-Aaron<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>A few Saturdays ago, I attended the Midwest Tool Collector&#8217;s Association (MWTCA) tool meet, and 